James de Villiers, News24 Paramedics protest over attacks against their colleagues. (Jenni Evans, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - Western Cape health department paramedics are getting anti-hijacking training after a crew was robbed while attending to a patient in Khayelitsha in December.&ldquo;We have introduced situational awareness training, including anti-hijacking training, for all staff and we also have targeted training around hotspots and incident management,&rdquo; department spokesperson Zimkhitha Mquteni said in a statement on Monday.READ: Paramedics protest as attack accused remain behind barsIn a separate incident on Monday, a group of armed men attacked paramedics employed by Cape Flats-based private ambulance service Melomed24. They were taking a colleague to Athlone at the time.Mquteni said paramedics had to get a police escort to enter certain areas.&ldquo;Our paramedics cannot attend to a call in an area deemed a red zone. They must get an escort from the South African Police Service.&rdquo;Ambulance windows had been tinted and covered with a smash-and-grab safety film.Mquteni said paramedics had been targeted 80 times between September 2015 and September 2016. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.